The '''Strategic Air Forces''' (FAS) ({{lang-fr|Commandement des Forces Aériennes Stratégiques (CFAS)}}) is a [[command (military formation)|command]] of the [[French Air Force]]. It was created on January 14, 1964, and directs France's [[Nuclear weapons and France|nuclear bombardment]] force.

== History ==
[[Image:Mirage IVP - CI.jpg|thumbnail|left|250px|[[Dassault Mirage IV|Mirage IV]]P of '''[[Escadron de Chasse 1/4 Gascogne|Escadron de Bombardement 1/91 Gascogne]]'''.]]
[[File:Mirage 2000N.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Dassault Mirage 2000N/2000D|Mirage 2000N]].]]

The first alert conducted by a bombardier [[Dassault Mirage IV|Mirage IV]] armed with [[AN-11 bomb|AN-11]] and a [[Boeing KC-135 Stratotanker|KC-135]] was executed on October 8, 1964: that date marked the beginning of operational permanence of French nuclear deterrence.<ref name="cfas_histo">[http://www.cfas.air.defense.gouv.fr/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=249&Itemid=0], Historique - Chronologie Détaillée, Historique - Chronologie Détaillée, 2006, Forces aériennes stratégiques, March 1, 2008</ref> Accordingly, the [[French aircraft carrier Verdun]] was envisaged to have deployed bomber aircraft at sea.

In April 1965, the initiative and confirmed will to establish a launch missile base « ground-to-ground strategic ballistics » (SSBS) ({{lang-fr|« sol-sol balistiques stratégiques »}}) under the Command of the Strategic Air Forces was executed. The latter was established on plateau Albion ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:plateau d'Albion|plateau d'Albion]]}}) of Aerial Base 200 Apt-Saint-Christol ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:base aérienne 200 Apt-Saint-Christol|base aérienne 200 Apt-Saint-Christol]]}}) and equipped with underground launch missile silos. The latter was an operational base from August 2, 1971, until dismantling on September 16, 1996.<ref name="cfas_histo" />

In the spring of 1966, with 9 [[List of French Air Force aircraft squadrons|Escadrons/Squadrons]] of [[Dassault Mirage IV|Mirage IV]], the ensemble of the first composite of the deterrence force was realized. In 1973, this deterrence force comprised 60 Mirage IV spread on nine bases of the French metropolitan territory.

Since the 1990s, aircraft of the Strategic Air Forces (FAS) intervene equally in foreign exterior operations in conventional combat missions as well.

== Organization ==

As of 1963 and until 2007, the Strategic Air Forces Command was headquartered at an underground command centre, which also welcomed the same year the Operations Center of the Strategic Air Forces ({{lang-fr|Centre d’Opérations des Forces Aériennes Stratégiques (COFAS)}}). The command post was accordingly built 50 meters under the ground, with a [[fallout shelter]] destined for the executive power in case of [[Nuclear warfare|Nuclear war]]; this command post was in full operational swing in 1967.<ref>[http://www.defense.gouv.fr/air/actus-air/taverny-interview-du-lieutenant-colonel-marc-longobardi], Taverny : Interview du lieutenant-colonel Marc Longobardi, Armée de l'air, July 26, 2011.</ref>

The general headquarter staff as of September 26, 2007 is situated on another Aerial Base<ref>[http://www.cfas.air.defense.gouv.fr/index.php/decouverte/situation-geographique], Situation géographique, Forces aériennes stratégiques, Armée de l'air, July 5, 2014.</ref> which was at origin, a secondary operations center. Since then, Aerial Bases change and relocate continuously while the concerned [[List of French Air Force aircraft squadrons|Air Fleet]] accordingly gets relocated on permanent or temporary basis.   
 
In 1968, at the peak of the highest alert phases, 62 [[Dassault Mirage IV|Mirage IV]] (out of which 9 on operational alert and capable of "being engaged in 5 minutes while the remainder would follow within the hour,<ref name="ISC01">La mise en place et le développement de la première generation [http://www.institut-strategie.fr/ihcc_nuc1_Vougny.html#Note1|site= institut de stratégie (ISC)], 2005, Philippe Vougny, général de corps aérien, Commandant les Forces Aériennes Stratégiques</ref> with the alert phase readiness increasing to 15 minutes, from 1964 until 1990 respectively) formed the nucleus of the 3 [[List of Escadres of the French Air Force|Escadres Bombardment]]  (EB) ( the 91st Bombardment Escadre ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:91e escadre de bombardement|91<sup>e</sup> Escadre de Bombardement]]}}), 91<sup>e</sup> EB - the 93rd Bombardment Escadre ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:93e escadre de bombardement|93<sup>e</sup> Escadre de Bombardement]]}}), 93 <sup>e</sup> EB - , and the 94th Bombardment Escadre ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:94e escadre de bombardement|94<sup>e</sup> Escadre de Bombardement]]}}), 94<sup>e</sup> EB) representing several bombardments units out of which 1 training center:<ref>Aerial Bombardment can include the designations of : [[List of Escadres of the French Air Force|Escadres Bombardment]] ({{lang-fr|Escadres de Bombardement, EB}}) units or refer to [[List of dissolved Squadrons of the French Air Force|Escadrons Bombardment]] ({{lang-fr|Escadrons de Bombardement, EB}}) units ((EB) designation as well) including training Escadrons Bombardment. In the [[French language]], there is even an Escadrilles Bombardment ({{lang-fr|Escadrilles de Bombardement}}). Accordingly an (EB) referring to a Bombardment unit can refer to any of a Escadre Bombardment (EB), Escadron Bombardment (EB) or Escadrille Bombardment (EB)</ref>

* EB 1/91 « Gascogne » formed 1 October 1964 at Air Base 118 Mont-de-Marsan at [[Mont-de-Marsan]]
* EB 2/94 « Marne » ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:Escadron de bombardement 2/94 Marne|Escadron de Bombardement 2/94 Marne]]}}) formed 24 February 1965 at [[Saint-Dizier – Robinson Air Base|Saint-Dizier Air Base]]
* EB 2/91 « Bretagne » formed 1 April 1965,<ref>[[List of dissolved Squadrons of the French Air Force|Dissolved]] in July 1996</ref> at [[Cazaux Air Base]] (BA 120) at [[Cazaux]].
* EB 3/91 « Beauvaisis » ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:Escadron de bombardement 3/91 Beauvaisis|Escadron de Bombardement 3/91 Beauvaisis]]}}) formed 1 June 1965 at Creil Air Base (BA 110). [[List of dissolved Squadrons of the French Air Force|Dissolved]] 30 June 1976.
* EB 3/93 « Sambre » le 6 July 1965 at Cambrai Air Base at [[Cambrai]]. [[List of dissolved Squadrons of the French Air Force|Dissolved]] 30 June 1976.
* EB 2/93 « Cevennes » formed 31 July 1965 at [[Base aérienne 115 Orange-Caritat|BA 115]] at [[Orange (Vaucluse)|Orange]]. Later redesignated « EB 3/91 Cévennes », the Escadron/Squadron was [[List of dissolved Squadrons of the French Air Force|dissolved]] in 1983.<ref name="Dissous en 1983">Dissolved in 1983</ref>
* EB 1/93 « Guyenne » le 15 October 1965 at [[Istres-Le Tube Air Base]] at [[Istres]]. Redesignated EB 1/94 on 30 June 1976 and transferred to [[Avord Air Base]].
* EB 1/94 « Bourbonnais » on 1 March 1966 at [[Avord Air Base]] at [[Avord]]. Dissolved on 30 June 1976
* EB 3/94 « Arbois » ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:Escadron de bombardement 3/94 Arbois|Escadron de bombardement 3/94 Arbois]]}}) on 1 June 1966<ref name="Dissous en 1983"/> at Aerial Base 116 Luxeuil-Saint Sauveur (BA 116) at [[Luxeuil-les-Bains|Luxeuil]]
* Instruction Center of Strategic Air Forces 328 ({{lang-fr|Centre d'instruction des Forces aériennes stratégiques 328 (CIFAS)}}) created on {{date|25|mai|1964}} at [[Bordeaux-Mérignac Air Base]]

Jointly, can be added 12 [[Boeing C-135 Stratolifter|Boeing C-135]]F aerial refuelling aircraft (of which 3 are on operational alert), dispersed into 3 Escadrons (ERV) :

* ERV 4/91 « Landes » created on 1 January 1964 at [[Mont-de-Marsan Air Base]] (BA 118) at [[Mont-de-Marsan]]
* ERV 4/93 « Aunis » created on 13 July 1965 on Aerial Base 125 Istres-Le Tubé at [[Istres]]. Later became ERV 4/94  « Bretagne »
* ERV 4/94 « Sologne » created on 15 April 1966 at [[Avord Air Base]] (BA 702) at [[Avord]].

In addition to the command, can be added Aerial Base Apt-Saint-Christol (BA 200), created in April 1967 under the Plateau d'Albion and transformed to a newly designated garrison as of June 16, 1999.<ref>QG Maréchal Kœnig is a garrison of the [[2nd Foreign Engineer Regiment]] 2<sup>e</sup> REG and a satellite station of the [[Directorate-General for External Security|DGSE]].</ref>

Independent from the Strategic Air Forces ({{lang-fr|Forces Aériennes Stratégiques, FAS}}), several installations were utilized by the latter:
* The center of experimentation of the Pacific (CEP) in [[French Polynesia]],<ref>Polynesia formerly garrisoned the [[5th Foreign Infantry Regiment]] 5<sup>e</sup> REI.</ref> created on July 1, 1963, composed of:
** one headquarter staff [[Papeete]],
** advanced Aerial Base 185 Hao ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:Base aérienne 185 Hao|BA 185]]}}) at [[Hao (French Polynesia)|Hao]] created on July 1, 1966 and dissolved in 2000,
** one testing surface area at [[Moruroa]]  
** one testing surface area at [[Fangataufa]]

In 2008, 60 [[Dassault Mirage 2000|Mirage 2000N]] of the Strategic Air Forces ({{lang-fr|Forces Aériennes Stratégiques, FAS}}) are stationed at two Aerial Bases. 
[[File:RafaleBGascogne.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Rafale B of the Escadron "Gascogne" & ASMPA.]]

In 2014, two nuclear squadrons equipped with more than 43 aircraft compose the Strategic Air Forces ({{lang-fr|Forces Aériennes Stratégiques, FAS}}) and number around 1400 personnel:<ref>Véronique GUILLEMARD, La France ne baisse pas la garde, LE FIGARO, 2015</ref>

*[[Escadron de Chasse 1/4 Gascogne]] ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:escadron de chasse 1/4 Gascogne|Escadron de Chasse 1/4 Gascogne]]}}) at [[Saint-Dizier – Robinson Air Base]], armed with more than 20 [[Dassault Rafale|Rafale B]] aircraft.<ref>[http://secretdefense.blogs.liberation.fr/defense/2010/06/le-rafale-prendra-lalerte-nucl%C3%A9aire-d%C3%A8s-le-1er-juillet.html], Le Rafale prendra l'alerte nucléaire dès le 1er juillet, Jean-Dominique Merchet, June 11, 2010, Libération</ref> 
*[[Escadron de Chasse 2/4 La Fayette]] ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:escadron de chasse 2/4 La Fayette|Escadron de Chasse 2/4 La Fayette]]}}) at [[Istres-Le Tubé Air Base]], armed with more than 20 [[Dassault Mirage 2000|Mirage 2000N]] aircraft.

In September 2018, the Mirage 2000N will be retired from service with the La Fayette Squadron converting to Rafale B. Both fighter squadrons will consolidate at the [[Saint-Dizier – Robinson Air Base]] in order to optimize training and logistics. Forward operating locations for dispersion of nuclear-armed Rafale flights will be retained at other air bases in line with the French redundancy practice to prevent taking out the aerial nuclear arm with a single massive strike.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.senat.fr/rap/r16-560/r16-560_mono.html#toc158|title=La nécessaire modernisation de la dissuasion nucléaire|website=www.senat.fr|language=fr|access-date=2018-04-18}}</ref>

Strategic Air Forces ({{lang-fr|Forces Aériennes Stratégiques, FAS}}) also consists of the [[Groupe de Ravitaillement en Vol 02.091 Bretagne]]<ref>The [[French language|French]] word "Ravitaillement" means "Supply" in [[English language|English]]. However, while the word "Ravitaillement" or "Supply" can be understood as designating Air Refueling, it can also designate within the context of the French Air Force, any sort of supply activity while Airborne.</ref> ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:groupe de ravitaillement en vol 02.091 Bretagne|Groupe de Ravitaillement en Vol 02.091 Bretagne]]}}) operating on 14 [[Boeing KC-135 Stratotanker|KC-135]] based on an Aerial Base and will be replaced by 12 [[Airbus A330 MRTT]] « Phénix » between 2018 and 2025.

=== Nuclear Arm Depots ===
[[Image:SG1059332.JPG|thumb|left|200px|A scale maquette of ASMPA.]]

During the retrieval service, between 1986 and 1989, of the numerous [[AN-22 bomb]] equipping the [[Dassault Mirage IV|Mirage IV]] bombardment units, a new generation of airborne [[Air-Sol Moyenne Portée|missile]] (ASMPA) arms were placed in service. These arms are maintained in operational conditioning and stocked in various designated special munitions depots ({{lang-fr|Dépôts Ateliers Munitions Spéciales DAMS}}), which are highly protected sites on different Aerial Bases.

As of 2010, the [[Air-Sol Moyenne Portée]] (ASMPA) of new generation is destined for the Strategic Air Forces (FAS) of the [[French Air Force]] and the French Naval  Nuclear Force ({{lang-fr|Force Aéronavale Nucléaire, FANU}}) of the [[French Navy]] ([[French Navy|Marine Nationale]]). The new equipment ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:tête nucléaire aéroportée|Tête Nucléaire Aéroportée]]}}) (TNA) is of an estimated power mass of 300 kt.

As of end of 2008 and until 2012, depots were reorganized at the occasion of the arrival of the ASMPA missile to be re-baptized under another ASMPA depot vector ({{lang-fr|« Dépôts vecteurs ASMPA » (DVA)}}). The special munitions depot ({{lang-fr|Dépôts Ateliers Munitions Spéciales DAMS}}) change frequently. The DVA is confined to the squadron during the placement in effect, while the TNA are handled differently, in a specialized zone that is very well protected.

